    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Just like the sharps, the flats follow a specific order as well. Starting from the note C, the sequence of flats goes B, E, A, D, G, C, and F. So if you see a key signature with two flats, it's either B-flat major or F major. If there are four flats, it's either E-flat major or B minor. The Circle of Fifths shows that keys with the same number of flats are related by a perfect fourth. For example, B-flat major and F major are a perfect fourth apart. So, if you're looking at a key signature with two flats, you could be in B-flat major or F major. And if you see a key signature with four flats, it's E-flat major or B minor. The Circle of Fifths helps you visualize this relationship and see that B-flat major and F major are a perfect fourth apart. It's a handy way to figure out the key of a piece when you're looking at the sheet music.",
